x4freetext: F.P., L.M.
The 150 MeV Geel Linac, GELINA,
operated with a burst width of 4.5 ns and a frequency
of 800 Hz, was used for the measurements.
.Uranium target, bombarded with 150 MeV electrons. The
neutrons were moderated for the 50 and 200 m trans-
mission measurements. In the 60 m capture measurement
the beam was collimated to 6.5 cm by copper and lead
cylinders.
.White neutron source.
Time-of-flight techniques, with five neutron
flight paths with lengths ranging from 28 to 400 m.
.A B4C slab, containing 10-B, being 5 mm thick, was
used to detect the neutrons in the 50 m transmission
measurements. The 478 keV gamma-ray from neutron cap-
ture in 10-B was detected by two 10.2 by 7.6 cm
NaI/Tl/ detectors, situated outside the
neutron beam.
A 25 mm thick NE 110 plastic scintillator,
viewed by four RCA 4516 photomultipliers tubes, was
used to detect the neutrons in the 200 and 400 m
transmission measurements. In addition, the beam was
filtered with  0.37 g/cm2 of uranium.
A BF3 detector was used to normalize the
sample-in and sample-out runs.
.A 0.4 g/cm2 B4C slab was placed in the beam to absorb
low-energy neutrons.
10.2 cm diameter by 7.6 cm thick C6D6 liquid
scintillators, placed with their axes perpendicular to
the neutron beam and 180 degrees apart, were used to
detect capture gamma-rays in the 60 m capture measure-
ment. A discriminator level of 150 keV electrons was
used.
.A B4C slab was used to measure the neutron flux in the
capture measurements.
In addition, a Li-glass detector was also used
for neutron flux determination.
The 478 keV photons associated
with this /n,a/-reaction was used to determine the
absolute neutron flux for the capture measurements.
.The samples were in form of chromium oxide, Cr2O3,
powder, enriched to a purity of 99.74%. The
powder was canned in thin aluminium containers of 8
or 3.5 cm diameter with 0.0114 and 0.0593 chromium
atoms/barn, respectively. The former was used for the
capture and 50 m transmission measurements, while the
latter was used for the 200 and 400 m transmission
measurement.
.The background in the transmission measurements was
determined from black resonance minima using Bi, Na
and S filters. The maximum dead-time correction in
these measurements was 10%.
.The background in the capture measurements was deter-
mined from black resonance minima using Ag, Bi, Co,
Na, S and W filters. The neutron flux curves obtained
from the B and Li data were corrected for background,
detection efficiency, self-screening and multiple
scattering effects, were found to agree within 3%
in the energy range 1 - 300 keV.
.No details given.
.Data taken from main ref.
